er object for testing instead.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test strategy**\\n\\nI’m questioning whether the public API should be changed since it involves package-private behavior. Should I remove the test and leave it uncovered? The user provided a specific failure, and they might want a fix. I could modify the test to prevent failure by using a fake driver, ensuring we still have coverage. The developer rules are strict, but the focus is on improving coverage. Existing tests use reflection for package-private operations, and it might be acceptable in this case, even with the reflections and warnings.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing constructor behavior**\\n\\nI'm looking at whether I can avoid using `Unsafe` by adjusting the constructor. It seems the constructor is failing because of a bug in `StandardReflectionDriver.findStaticMethod`, which shouldn't be finding `Class.forName` with one argument. It catches the error from `forName0`, leading to the fallback that also fails due to a `NoSuchMethodException`. Since it's not able to invoke the constructor, it looks like I'll need to use `Unsafe` or implement a reflection factory instead.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_vSEimzMVFGJIXHJzYRrA8v9m|fc_04c366b99325990b016a245b11e9348193a56ecfe8bf597c3d", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.github.classgraph/classgraph/4.8.165/src/test/java/io_github_classgraph/classgraph/JVMDriverReflectionDriverTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import io.github.classgraph.ClassGraph;\nimport io.github.classgraph.ClassGraph.CircumventEncapsulationMethod;\nimport io.github.toolfactory.jvm.DefaultDriver;\nimport sun.misc.Unsafe;\n", "newText": "import io.github.classgraph.ClassGraph;\nimport io.github.classgraph.ClassGraph.CircumventEncapsulationMethod;\nimport sun.misc.Unsafe;\n"}, {"oldText": "        final Object jvmDriver = new DefaultDriver();\n\n        setField(driverClass, reflectionDriver, \"driver\", jvmDriver